sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: APT37 has likely been active since at least 2012 and focuses on targeting the public and private sectors primarily in South Korea. In 2017, APT37 expanded its targeting beyond the Korean peninsula to include Japan, Vietnam and the Middle East, and to a wider range of industry verticals, including chemicals, electronics, manufacturing, aerospace, automotive and healthcare entities

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Potential Persistence Attempt Via Existing Service Tampering
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects the modification of an existing service in order to execute an arbitrary payload when the service is started or killed as a potential method for persistence.

match_context.values: @{EventID=1; CommandLine="C:\Windows\sysnative\cmd.exe" /c cd /d "C:\Program Files (x86)\ConsulSoft\StatRKZU\Export" && expand -F:* install.cab "C:\Program Files (x86)\ConsulSoft\StatRKZU\Export" && ren wiasvc64.dll wiasvc.dll && wiasvc.bat; Image=C:\Windows\sysnative\cmd.exe}

sigma_analysis_results.rule_description: Detects process creation events that use the Sysnative folder (common for CobaltStrike spawns)

sigma_analysis_results.rule_title: Potential Homoglyph Attack Using Lookalike Characters in Filename
sigma_analysis_results.rule_description:
Detects the presence of unicode characters which are homoglyphs, or identical in appearance, to ASCII letter characters.
This is used as an obfuscation and masquerading techniques. Only "perfect" homoglyphs are included; these are characters that
are indistinguishable from ASCII characters and thus may make excellent candidates for homoglyph attack characters.
Detects changes to the "ServiceDLL" value related to a service in the registry. This is often used as a method of persistence.
Detects the creation of a new office macro files on the systems
